ce:section.ce:para:
The time-resolved FL attenuation curves of N-CQDs at various concentrations were assessed at various emission and excitation wavelengths to further clarify the explanation of the concentration-dependent FL characteristics, as illustrated in Fig. 11
                        . From low to high concentration, the four N-CQDs had average FL lifetimes of 10.33, 10.07, 9.16, and 9.13 ns, respectively (Table 2
                        ). The FL lifetime of the emission center was observed to decrease with increasing concentrations, likely attributed to energy or electron transfers between particles [44,45]. The FL lifetime analyses of solutions containing four distinct concentrations of N-CQDs demonstrated a strong fit for the double exponential function. This suggests the presence of two distinct emission sites, namely the intrinsic state emission (represented by τ1) and the surface defect emission (represented by τ2). The emission of the intrinsic state was triggered by the sp2 carbon domain, whereas the emission of the surface defect was caused by either the carbon backbone or the functional groups related to oxygen or nitrogen [18,27,46–49]. The FL emission of monodisperse N-CQDs is predominantly driven by the surface state emission at low concentration, as evidenced by an increase in the amount of τ2 components relative to τ1 components as the concentration was increased from 0.01 to 0.1 mg/mL. At concentrations ranging from 0.5 to 2.0 mg/mL, it was observed that the τ1 components exceeded the τ2 components. This finding suggests that the FL emission of N-CQDs is primarily attributed to the sp2 carbon domain of the intrinsic state. At elevated concentrations, the proximity between N-CQD particles increases, leading to the gradual enlargement of aggregates. This phenomenon results in the sp2 carbon domain of aggregates being larger than that of single N-CQDs, which aligns with the findings of UV–Vis and TEM analysis. Consequently, as the concentration of N-CQDs increased, their FL emission progressively shifted from the surface defect state to the intrinsic state emission.
